Example: Balancing an Image Datastore

clear variables
 
% locally, our image files will be in a "Food_dataset" folder
bucket = "Food_dataset";
As an example, we will use images of food, as this data is available in the Matlab DeepLearning toolbox
tic;
% if the data is not already in our local folder, we will download it
if ~exist(bucket,"dir")
zipFile = matlab.internal.examples.downloadSupportFile('nnet','data/ExampleFoodImageDataset.zip');
try
unzip(zipFile,bucket);
catch
%
end
end
toc;
Elapsed time is 0.002889 seconds.

Creation of the imageDatastore

we create the datastore based on the name of the folders to determine the labels of the classes.
tic;
imds_Food = imageDatastore(bucket,'IncludeSubfolders',true,'LabelSource','foldernames').shuffle;
toc;
Elapsed time is 0.082321 seconds.

Characterisation of the initial imageDatastore

the number of images per class in the datastore is determined
numObsPerClass = countEachLabel(imds_Food);
display(numObsPerClass)
numObsPerClass = 3Ã—2 table
 LabelCount
1caesar_salad26
2caprese_salad15
3french_fries20
The initial image datastore has unbalanced classes.
This is not dramatic here; but in a real case, with many images, the difference in the number of images per class can be problematic.

Preview

It is always useful to preview a few images from each class.
IMDS.previewClasses(imds_Food)

Balancing the imageDatastore

As the imageDatastore has unbalanced image classes, they can be rebalanced by duplicating the images present to reach the maximum number observed
tic;
imds_B = IMDS.balanceImageDatastore(imds_Food)
imds_B =
